name: Adrian John Williams
summary:
Mr Williams has been an MP since 2009 having served as a Member of the Portfolio Committee on Public Service and Administration as well as the Portfolio Committee on Co-Operative Governance and Traditional Affairs. He joined the ANC, SACP and Chemical Workers Industrial Union in 1990 where he served as the ANC Secunda branch treasurer (1991-1992). Mr Williams was also active in the Yeoville branch of the ANC and SACP Structures (1993-1997). He has served as the SACP Secunda branch Secretary (1998), ANC Secunda Branch Secretary (1999), as a Mpumalanga additional PEC member (1999-2001), as Mpumalanga SACP Provincial Treasurer (2002-2005), a SAMWU Full-time Shop-steward (Govan Mbeki Local Municipality) and as the SACP Mpumalanga Provincial deputy Secretary (2006-to-date). (Source: anc.org.za)

Adrian John Williams's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Adrian-John-Williams-Attendance-2013 "Adrian John Williams") and [2012](/file_archive/Adrian-John-Williams-Attendance-2012 "Adrian John Williams").

summary:
Anchen Margaretha Dreyer's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Anchen-Margaretha-Dreyer-Attendance-2013 "Anchen Dreyer") and [2012](/file_archive/Anchen-Margaretha-Dreyer-Attendance-2012 "Anchen Dreyer").

Ms Dreyer was born in the then Transvaal. She obtained a Masters degree in clinical psychology from Rand Afrikaans University (RAU). She entered the political scene in 1978 working as a volunteer for the old PFP. She was first elected as a DA Member of Parliament, where she served as the DA’s spoke person on Labour. In 2009 she was re-elected to Parliament as Shadow Minister of Public Service and Administration and is currently serving as the Shadow Minister of Public Works. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za)

name: Andricus Pieter Van der Westhuizen
summary:
Andricus Pieter Van der Westhuizen's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Andricus-Van-der-Westhuizen-Attendance-2013 "Andricus Van der Westhuizen") and [2012](/file_archive/Andricus-Van-der-Westhuizen-Attendance-2012 "Andricus Van der Westhuizen").

Mr van der Westhuizen was raised in Stellenbosch in the Western Cape. He obtained a BCom degree and a Diploma in Higher Education, and a Masters Degree in Educational Leadership and Development from Stellenbosch University. Before entering the political arena, Mr van der Westhuizen worked at Old Mutual as a trainee manager for a very brief period and opted for a career in the education sector. He was later appointed as the Deputy-Chief Education Specialist in the Directorate: Quality Assurance of the Western Cape Education Department. Before his election to Parliament in 2009, Mr van der Westhuizen was involved in local government and got elected as the DA’s speaker of the Stellenbosch Council. He is currently appointed as the Shadow Deputy Minister of Labour. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za).

name: Andries Carl Nel
summary:
Deputy Minister Nel has held his current portfolio since May 2009 and has been a Member of Parliament for the African National Congress (ANC) since 1994. He holds a Bachelor of Civil Law from the University of Pretoria. He served as whip of Portfolio Committee on Justice and House Whip. Between 2006 and 2007 he served as Acting Chief Whip of the African National Congress (ANC) and as a Chairperson of House of the National Assembly between 2008 and 2009. He had served on various Portfolio Committees including Justice and Constitutional Development, Correctional Services, Health, Home Affairs, and Communications. He also served as a member of the Standing Committee on Public Accounts (SCOPA). Deputy Minister Nel was involved in the End Conscription Campaign, and had been active in politics since high school in Sao Paulo, Brazil. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Andries Carl Nel's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/andries-carl-nel-attendance-2013 "andries carl nel attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/andries-carl-nel-attendance-2012 "andries carl nel attendance").

name: Annelie Lotriet
summary:
Annelie Lotriet's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Annelie-Lotriet-Attendance-2013 "Annelie Lotriet") and [2012](/file_archive/Annelie-Lotriet-Attendance-2012 "Annelie Lotriet").

Dr Lotriet was born in Johannesburg. She completed her post-secondary education at Rand Afrikaans University where she graduated with a BA degree in Languages. Annelie continued her studies and completed a Doctorate degree in Education specializing in higher education. Before making her entrance into South African politics she worked in academia and lectured at both Vista University and the University of the Free State. In 2000 she was appointed as a ward councilor for the DA in Mangaung and served on number of provincial and national committees, boards and associations and are presently serving as the Shadow Minister of Higher Education. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za).

name: Annelizé van Wyk
summary:
Ms van Wyk was born in Pretoria. After completing her studies at the University of Potchefstroom, she worked for Military Intelligence. Thereafter, she accepted a position at the Human Sciences Research Council. She joined the National Party in 1987 and served as member of the Gauteng Legislature from 1994-1997. She then resigned to help Roelf Meyer form the UDM. She joined the ANC in 2003. 

Annelizé van Wyk's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Annelize-van-Wyk-Attendance-2013 "Annelize van Wyk") and [2012](/file_archive/Annelize-van-Wyk-Attendance-2012 "Annelize van Wyk").

name: Annette Steyn
summary:
Annette Steyn's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Annette-Steyn-Attendance-2013 "Annette Steyn") and [2012](/file_archive/Annette-Steyn-Attendance-2012 "Annette Steyn").

Ms Steyn was first elected to Parliament in 2009. She has executed duties as Councillor for the Gariep Municipality and was appointed as the chairperson of the DA in the Eastern Cape. Annette is currently serving as the DA’s Shadow Minister of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za).

name: Annette Theresa Lovemore
summary:
Annette Theresa Lovemore's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Annette-Theresa-Lovemore-Attendance-2013 "Annette Theresa Lovemore") and [2012](/file_archive/Annette-Theresa-Lovemore-Attendance-2012 "Annette Theresa Lovemore").

Ms Lovemore is currently appointed as the DA’s Shadow Minister of Basic Education. Prior to her election to Parliament in 2009, she served as a Councilor in the Nelson Mandela Bay Municipality.

name: Armiston Watson
summary:
Mr Watson matriculated in 1962 and went on to further his studies in commerce and management and worked at the maize board until 1965. Mr Watson's political career began in 1965 as a member of the National Party.He served at local government level in Mpumalanga for many years and on several different councils. He joined the DA in 2000 and went on to hold several high profile positions in the Mpumalanga Provincial structures, including Provincial Director. Mr Watson was first elected to parliament in 2000 and then again in 2004 as a permanent delegate to the NCOP for the Mpumalanga Province where he was appointed DA Leader in the NCOP. He sits on the NCOP Select Committees on Land, Agriculture, Water Affairs, Nature Conservation, Tourism and Public services. Mr Watson was re-appointed as DA Leader in the NCOP on his re-election to Parliament in 2009. He has a love of languages and speaks many fluently including isiXhosa, isiZulu, Sesotho, Ndebele, siSwati and Setswana. He loves nature conservation, travel and outdoor living. Source: www.da.org.za/our_people 

Armiston Watson's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Armiston-Watson-Attendance-2013 "Armiston Watson") and [2012](/file_archive/Armiston-Watson-Attendance-2012 "Armiston Watson").

name: Arron Cecil Steyn
summary:
Arron Cecil Steyn's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Arron-Cecil-Steyn-Attendance-2013 "Arron Cecil Steyn") and [2012](/file_archive/Arron-Cecil-Steyn-Attendance-2012 "Arron Cecil Steyn").

Before entering the political arena, Mr Steyn was employed as a civil engineer and provided architectural consulting services. This led to the establishment of his own company of which he became the Managing Director and was also involved in project management in the oil industry. He was elected to Parliament in 2004 and was appointed as a representative of the DA in the Gauteng Legislature from 1999 to 2004. Mr Steyn is currently appointed as the Shadow Deputy Minister of Education for the DA. Source: DA (www.da.org.za).

name: Arthur Roy Ainslie
summary:
Mr. Arthur Roy Ainslie has been an MP since 1999. He holds a BA from UCT, and Economic and Public Finance Certificate from Unisa and a B. Com honours degree from UWC. He was a member of KwaZulu-Natal MPL from 1994 to 1999 and has appeared on the PC Environmental Affairs and Tourism Committee, the PC Public Works and the PC Science and Technology. Mr. Ainslie is currently the ANC Greater Kwadukuza Regional Treasurer, Umhlanga Community Development Trust Chairperson, ANC Kwadukuza region KZN ex-officio and the Joint editor of Journal Natal. He is interested in development, poverty elimination and job creation and would like to see more people participating in government programmes. Source: ANC (www.anc.org.za)

Arthur Roy Ainslie's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Arthur-Roy-Ainslie-Attendance-2013 "Arthur Roy Ainslie Attendance") and [2012](/file_archives/Arthur-Roy-Ainslie-Attendance-2012 "Arthur Roy Ainslie Attendance").

name: Ayanda Dlodlo
summary:
Deputy Minister Dlodlo is the Deputy Minister of Public Service and Administration of the Republic of South Africa since 1 November 2010. She holds a number of post graduate qualifications in Management Development; Business Management and Executive Development Programme. Her colorful CV includes working for public enterprises as Telkom, and Portnet; Sanlam in various portfolios such as Human Resources, Transport, Strategic information and Industrial Relations. She is an ex-Umkhonto Wesizwe cadre. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Ayanda Dlodlo's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/ayanda-dlodlo-attendance-2013 "ayanda dlodlo attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/ayanda-dlodlo-attendance-2012 "ayanda dlodlo attendance").

name: Barbara Thomson
summary:
Deputy Minister Thompson was born on 03 February 1954. She has been a Member of Parliament since 1995 and she was Chairperson of the Portfolio Committee on Women, Children and People with Disabilities. She served various Portfolio Committees including Public Works, Land and Agriculture, Joint Monitoring Committee on the Improvement of the Quality of Life and Status of Women. During her political career she has served in various positions such as a Regional Secretary of ANC Women League (ANCWL) in KZN. The Deputy Minister obtained a Certificate in Leadership Comunication and a Certificate in Government and Business Policy from Rhodes University. She has dedicated her strength in the areas of Skills Development for Women and Rural Development. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Barbara Thomson's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Barbara-Thomson-Attendance-2013 "Barbara Thomson") and [2012](/file_archive/Barbara-Thomson-Attendance-2012 "Barbara Thomson").

name: Bathabile Olive Dlamini
summary:
Minister Dlamini holds a Bachelor of Arts Degree in Social Studies from the University of Zululand. She became an active member of the Idlangamabala Youth at Imbali's St Marks Anglican Church as well as the South African Students Congress. She worked with various structures including the Congress of South Africa Trade Unions. She became part of the interim leadership formed to build the ANC Women’s League in the KZN regions in 1991, and became Deputy Secretary General of the ANCWL in 1993. She became a member of NEC of the ANC as well as the National Working Committee in 2007. Source: (Info.gov.za) 

Bathabile Olive Dlamini's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/bathabile-olive-dlamini-attendance-2013 "bathabile olive dlamini attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/bathabile-olive-dlamini-attendance-2012 "bathabile olive dlamini attendance").

name: Beauty Nomhle Dambuza
summary: Ms Dambuza earned a Certificate in Economics & Finance. An ANC Activist since 1980, and an MP since 2004, she has held various positions as Chairperson and Secretary of Branch. In addition, Ms Dambuza was the elected Regional Treasurer of Sisonke REC (1998-2005), and has exerted her influence through several initiatives including the Community Development Project.

name: Beauty Nomvuzo Dlulane
summary:
Ms Dlulane has been a Member of Parliament since 2003. She earned her Business Studies certificate from Damelin College. She served on the Select Committee on Public Services, the Select Committee on Land and Environmental Affairs and the Joint Committee on Ethics and Members' Interests. She was also the Chairperson for the ANCWL Gauteng as well as the ANCWL Chairperson Greater Soweto sub-region. 

Beauty Nomvuzo Dlulane's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/beauty-nomvuzo-dlulane-attendance-2013 "beauty nomvuzo dlulane attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/beauty-nomvuzo-dlulane-attendance-2012 "beauty nomvuzo dlulane attendance").

name: Benedict Anthony Duke Martins
summary:
Minister Martins was born on 02 September 1956. He holds a Master of Law degree in International Law from the University of Cape Town; and a Bachelor of Law degree from the University of Natal. He was a member of the Black Consciousness Movement in the 1970s. Between 1983 and 1991 he was charged and imprisoned for eight years in Robben Island and Johannesburg. He had been a Member of Parliament since 1994, and had chaired the Portfolio Committee on Home Affairs. The Minister is a member of the Political Bureau and Central Committee of the South African Communist Party (SACP). Source: (info.gov.za) 

Benedict Anthony Duke Martins' plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Benedict-Anthony-Duke-Martins-Attendance-2013 "Benedict Anthony Duke Martins Attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/Benedict-Anthony-Duke-Martins-Attendance-2012 "Benedict Anthony Duke Martins Attendance").

summary: Ben Turok's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Benjamin-Turok-Attendance-2013 "Ben Turok") and [2012](/file_archive/Benjamin-Turok-Attendance-2012 "Ben Turok").

name: Bertha Peace Mabe
summary: Ms Mabe was born on 18 September 1976 in Magaliesburg. She attained a Degree in Public Administration from the University of Pretoria and became a Member of Parliament in 2009. Ms Mabe also serves on the Select Committee on Land and Environmental Affairs, Agriculture, Forestry & Fisheries, Rural Development & Land Reform, Water & Environmental Affairs, is on the ANC Finance Committee, and has been a member of the ANC Youth League.

name: Bhekizizwe Abram Radebe
summary: Bhekiziswe Abram Radebe's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/bhekiziswe-abram-radebe-attendance-2013 "Radebe Attendance 2013") and [2012](/file_archive/bhekiziswe-abram-radebe-attendance-2012 "Radebe Attendance 2012").

name: Bhekizizwe Zeblon Zulu
summary:
Mr Zulu has been an MP sin 1999, serving on the Select Committees on Safety and Security, Correctional Services, Sport, and Education and Recreation. He is currently a Member of the Provincial Executive Council and the Regional Working Committee of the ANC in KwaZulu Natal, Zulu Royal Family Chair of Members and is a Member of the South African Communist Party. His policy interests are rural issues. 

Bhekizizwe Zeblon Zulu's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Bhekizizwe-Zeblon-Zulu-Attendance-2013 "Bhekizizwe Zeblon Zulu") and [2012](/file_archive/Bhekizizwe-Zeblon-Zulu-Attendance-2012 "Bhekizizwe Zeblon Zulu").

name: Bomo Edna Edith Molewa
summary:
Minister Molewa was born on 23 March 1957. The provincial Chairperson of the African National Congress WL (NW) is currently studying towards a B.Com degree with UNISA. She taught at Moloto and Makaunyane Secondary Schools from 1976 to 1981, but also was involved in the underground structures of the liberation movement since 1976 until 1990. Prior to her appointment as Minister of Water and Environmental Affairs, she served as Minister of Social Development and Premier of North West. She was the first woman Chairperson of the Portfolio Committee on Trade and Industry from 1994 to 1996. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Bomo Edna Edith Molewa's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Bomo-Edna-Edith-Molewa-Attendance-2013 "Bomo Edna Edith Molewa Attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/Bomo-Edna-Edith-Molewa-Attendance-2012 "Bomo Edna Edith Molewa Attendance")

summary: Bongekile Jabulile Dlomo's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/bongekile-jabulile-dlomo-attendance-2013 "bongekile jabulile dlomo attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/bongekile-jabulile-dlomo-attendance-2012 "bongekile jabulile dlomo attendance").

name: Bongi Maria Ntuli
summary:
Deputy Minister Ntuli holds a B.Com Honours degree in Information Systems from University of the Western Cape and obtained an Advanced Diploma in Economic policy from the same institution. She was trained in Managing economic strategies and micro economic policy reform; and in Implementation of sustainable strategies in a globalising world from Williams College in US. She became a Member of Parliament in 1994, and had served on various Parliamentary Committees, including the Joint Monitoring Committee on Improvement of Quality of Life and Status of women; and Portfolio Committee on Trade and Industry. Prior to her appointment, she was Deputy Minister of Trade and Industry from 2009 until 2010. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Bongi Maria Ntuli's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/bongi-maria-ntuli-attendance-2013 "bongi maria ntuli attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/bongi-maria-ntuli-attendance-2012 "bongi maria ntuli attendance").

name: Bonginkosi Emmanuel Nzimande
summary:
Minister Nzimande was born on 14 April 1958. The current General Secretary of the South African Communist Party holds a Doctorate in Philosophy specializing in Sociology from the University of Natal. Dr Nzimande lectured at the University of Zululand in 1985, and was a lecturer for Industrial Psychology at the University of Natal in 1987. He had served Parliament as Chairperson of the Parliamentary Select Committee on Education, and had held various leadership positions at SA universities. He has written a book titled "Children of wars: the impact of violence on schooling in Natal". Source: (info.gov.za) 

Bonginkosi Emmanuel Nzimande's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Bonginkosi-Emmanuel-Nzimande-Attendance-2013 "Bonginkosi Emmanuel Nzimande Attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/Bonginkosi-Emmanuel-Nzimande-Attendance-2012 "Bonginkosi Emmanuel Nzimande Attendance").

summary: Bulelwa Tinto's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Bulelwa-Tinto-Attendance-2013 "Bulelwa Tinto") and [2012](/file_archive/Bulelwa-Tinto-Attendance-2012 "Bulelwa Tinto").

name: Cassel Charlie Mathale
summary: Mr Mathale was born on 23 January 1961. He completed his secondary education at Phangasasa High School in Tzaneen and continued his studies at the University of the Western Cape where he obtained a Bachelor of Arts degree. He was the Premier of Limpopo Province until July 2013. Mr Mathale was in addition appointed as the Provincial Secretary for the ANC in Limpopo and a member of the ANCYL National Executive Committee from 1996 to 1998. He has served on the Portfolio Committees on Human Settlements, and Science and Technology as a representative for the ANC and executing duties as the Provincial Chairperson of Limpopo for the ANC.

name: Cecil Valentine Burgess
summary:
Mr Burgess received his BA from the University of South Africa (Unisa). He was a member of the Portfolio Committee on Joint Constitutional Review, the Portfolio Committee on Correctional Services and the Portfolio Committee on Justice & Constitutional Development. Mr Burgess also practices law, previously having worked as a human rights attorney and currently serving as a practicing attorney for Burgess & Associates. 

Cecil Valentine Burgess' plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/cecil-valentine-burgess-attendance-2013 "cecil valentine burgess attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/cecil-valentine-burgess-attendance-2012 "cecil valentine burgess attendance").

summary: Celiwe Qhamkile Madlopha's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/celiwe-qhamkile-madlopha-attendance-2013 "celiwe qhamkile madlopha attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/celiwe-qhamkile-madlopha-attendance-2012 "celiwe qhamkile madlopha attendance").

name: Charel Jacobus De Beer
summary: Mr De Beer received his BA from the University of Port Elizabeth. He was an MPL in the Northern Cape Provincial Legislature (1998–99, 2000-04), an ANC Member of the Provincial Legislature (2004-09) and chaired the Portfolio Committee for Safety and Liaison (2004-09).

name: Charles Danny Kekana
summary: Charles Danny Kekana's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/charles-danny-kekana-attendance-2013 "charles danny kekana attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/charles-danny-kekana-attendance-2012 "charles danny kekana attendance").

name: Christopher Lancaster Gololo
summary:
Mr Gololo joined the ANC in 1977 in Tanzania having worked for the ANC in Mpumalanga on return from exile in 1993. He spent his exile years in Tanzania, Cuba, Czechoslovakia and India. Mr Gololo also served as the Regional Membership Administrator of the ANC (1994-2004) before joining Parliament. His Matric was obtained from the Bunya Secondary School thereafter obtaining a certificate in Electrotechnics from Eduardo Garcia Delgado in Cuba, a certificate in Administration in Czechoslavakia, a Diploma in Management from India and a Diploma in Management from the Institute of Development Management in Morogoro, Tanzania) (Source: anc.org.za)

Christopher Lancaster Gololo's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/christopher-lancaster-gololo-attendance-2013 "christopher lancaster gololo attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/christopher-lancaster-gololo-attendance-2012 "christopher lancaster gololo attendance").

name: Charles Nqakula
summary: Mr Nqakula started his career as a journalist, covering political news from 1966 to 1982. He began his political career as a Publicity Secretary for the United Democratic Front (1983) and joined the South African Communist Party in 1991 but was appointed as a MP and Member of the National Executive Committee for the ANC in 1994. Mr Nqakula was selected as a Parliamentary Councilor for the Office of the President in 1999 and became a Deputy Minister for the Department of Home Affairs in 2001. In 2002 he became the Minister for Safety and Security and thereafter the Minister of Defense (2008-2009). He has been the National Chairman for the South African Communist Party since 1999; Political Advisory to the Presidency since 2009; and the High Commissioner for the Republic of Mozambique since May 2012. (Source: whoswho.co.za)

name: Cornelia Carol September
summary:
Minister September occupied the Human Settlements portfolio following the recall of Minister Sexwale on 10 July 2013. She had been a Member of Parliament for the African National Congress (ANC) since 1999, and served on various Portfolio Committees. She had formerly served as Chairperson for the Portfolio Committee on Water Affairs & Forestry, but also served as Chief Whip in the National Assembly from 2004 until her appointment. The Minister obtained a Masters degree in Economics from Warwick University. The former trade unionist worked at Rex TrueForm factory for longer than 20 years. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Cornelia Carol September's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/cornelia-carol-september-attendance-2013 "September Attendance 2013") and [2012](/file_archive/cornelia-carol-september-attendance-2012 "September Attendance 2012").

name: Dalitha Fiki Boshigo
summary:
Ms. Dalitha Fiki Boshigo is an MP in the ANC parliamentary caucus. She has a diploma in Business Management and certificates in Social Development, Sector Policing and Rural Development Management. In the past, Ms. Boshigo served as the Treasurer of the former Eastern region of the ANC and worked with the Sekhukhune Organising team and UDF Community Forum. She is currently a member of the PC on Co-operative Governance and Traditional Affairs and the PC on Public Service and Administration. Source: ANC (www.anc.org.za)

name: Darryl Arthur Worth
summary: Mr Waters was born on 30 June 1967 in England and came to South Africa with his parents in 1972. He was elected to Parliament in 1999, and was later appointed the DA spokesperson on Child Abuse. In 2004 he became the Social Development spokesperson. Currently he is the shadow Minister of Social Development. Source: www.da.org.za/our_people and en.wikipedia.org/wiki Written Questions Member's Interests Hansard Appearances Committee Appearances Voting

summary:
David Christie Ross's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/David-Christie-Ross-Attendance-2013 "David Christie Ross") and [2012](/file_archive/David-Christie-Ross-Attendance-2012 "David Christie Ross").

Mr Ross is currently serving as the DA’s Shadow Deputy Minister of Finance.

name: David Douglas Des Van Rooyen
summary:
Mr Van Rooyen got involved in politics in the mid - 1980s. He was an MK operative and soldier, and held various leadership positions in COSAS, Khutsong Student Congress, UDF Representative, NUM Member. He also held a number of leadership positions in the ANC from 1994 to 2007. Mr Van Rooyen holds an advance Business Management Diploma, a Diploma in Municipal Governance, a certificate in Municipal Governance, a certificate in Councillor Development, a certificate in Municipal Finance, a certificate in Economic & Public Finance and a Masters Degree in Public Development and Management. He has personal interests in soccer, golf, tennis, reading and hunting. Source: www.anc.org.za/caucus Written Questions Member's Interests Hansard Appearances Committee Appearances Voting

David Douglas Van Rooyen's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/David-Douglas-Van-Rooyen-Attendance-2013 "David Douglas Van Rooyen") and [2012](/file_archive/David-Douglas-Van-Rooyen-Attendance-2012 "David Douglas Van Rooyen").

name: David John Maynier
summary:
Mr Maynier is a Shadow Minister of Defence and Military Veterans for the Democratic Alliance. After matriculating in 1986, he completed his 'national service' as a submarine officer and navy diver in the South African Navy in 1989. In 1996 he graduated from the University of Cape Town with honours, where he majored in politics and economics. In 2008, David graduated with a Masters Degree in Public Administration from Harvard University. After returning home, Mr Maynier appointed as campaign manager in the Western Cape where the party won an outright majority. He was elected as a Member of Parliament in 2009. Source: www.da.org.za/our_people 

David Maynier's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/David-John-Maynier-Attendance-2013 "David Maynier") and [2012](/file_archive/David-John-Maynier-Attendance-2012 "David Maynier")

summary:
Deborah Anne Schäfer's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Deborah-Anne-Schafer-Attendance-2013 "Deborah Anne Schafer") and [2012](/file_archive/Deborah-Anne-Schafer-Attendance-2012 "Deborah Anne Schafer").

Ms Schafer was born in Pietermaritzburg and completed her secondary education in Cape Town. She obtained a BA degree in English and Psychology from the University of Cape Town and later completed an LLB degree.  She practiced law for a period of twelve years prior to starting her political career.  Debbie joined the DP in 1999 and served as a ward councilor. She was first elected to Parliament in 2009 and is currently executing duties as the Shadow Deputy Minister of Justice and Constitutional Development and also serves as the Deputy Chairperson of the Regional Executive in the City of Cape Town, a member of the Provincial Disciplinary Committee and the Registrar of the DA Federal Legal Commission. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za).

name: Deidre Carter
summary: Deputy General Secretary of COPE, Ms Deidre Carter, hails from the Free State, but currently lives in KwaZulu-Natal. She has extensive administrative experience and is skilled in the areas of human resources, credit control, sales, fleet control and the like. Ms Carter represents COPE as a Member of Parliament. She serves on the Portfolio Committee for Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries, as well as Rural Development. She is an active motorcyclist who participates in many road safety projects and charity runs.

name: Denise Robinson
summary:
Denise Robinson's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Denise-Robinson-Attendance-2013 "Denise Robinson") and [2012](/file_archive/Denise-Robinson-Attendance-2012 "Denise Robinson").

Ms Robinson grew up in Queenstown but has lived in Cape Town for many years. She completed her post-secondary education at Rhodes University and attained a Bachelor of Arts degree majoring in English and History and in addition completed a University Education Diploma. Prior to joining South African politics, Ms Robinson worked as a teacher and later started a career as a language adviser and translator. On her entry into politics in 1998, she became a Proportional Representative councilor for the DP and was elected as ward councilor for the City of Cape Town in 2000 as a representative for the DA. Denise was appointed as the Shadow Minister of Women, Youth, Children and People with Disabilities in 2009 and is currently serving as the Deputy Shadow Minister of Health for the DA. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za).

name: Derek André Hanekom
summary:
Minister Hanekom was born on 13 January 1953. He attended school at Jan van Riebeeck Secondary school, and after his compulsory conscription, traveled abroad. He worked for various organisations and on farms, factories and building sites. He returned to SA and practised farming for six years. He worked with the trade union movement in Johannesburg before being deported to Zimbabwe with his wife in 1987. He returned in 1990, and worked at the headquarters of the ANC, where he was responsible for policy formulation on land and agricultural matters. Source: (info.gov.za)

Derek Andre Hanekom's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/derek-andre-hanekom-attendance-2013 "derek andre hanekom attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/derek-andre-hanekom-attendance-2012 "derek andre hanekom attendance").

summary:

Kohler Barnard hails from Port Elizabeth. Prior to joining the DA in 2004 she worked as a radio and print journalist and has travelled abroad extensively. She previously worked for the SABC, SAfm radio and became the Chairperson of BEMAWU-KZN (Broadcast, Electronic Media and Allied Workers Union) in 2001. Whilst employed at the SABC she became one of the founding members of the inaugural SABC HIV/Aids Committee and in addition served on the Gender Committee, the Security Task Force and Regional Management Committee. After being re-elected to Parliament in 2009, Dianne was appointed as the Shadow Minister of Police. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za).

name: Dina Deliwe Pule
summary:
Ms Pule started her political career while in college as the Secretary of the Student Representative Council at the Eastern Cape Mango College of Education (1987 – 1988). She was a Founder-Member of the South African National Students' Congress. From 2008 to 2009 she was a Member of the Executive Council within the Sports Arts and Recreation branch for the Government of South Africa. Ms Pule has served in various ministerial positions, including, Deputy Minister of Communications (2009 – 2010), Deputy Minister in the Presidency for Performance Monitoring and Evaluation (2010 – 2011) and Minister of Communications (2011 to July 2013). As of 2014 she had served as a Member of the Provincial Executive Council for Agriculture and Land Administration in Mpumalanga. (Source: whoswho.co.za)

Dina Deliwe Pule's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/dina-deliwe-pule-attendance-2013 "Pule Attendance 2013") and [2012](/file_archive/dina-deliwe-pule-attendance-2012 "Pule Attendance 2012").

name: Dion Travers George
summary:
Mr George went to Wits University, after completing his undergraduate degree and compulsory national service; he entered the financial services industry where he built his career. During this time he was also a community activist, this later prompted his political career. He further acquired a BA (Hons), MBA (Wits) and DBL (Economics) degrees and an Advanced Certificate in Municipal Governance. His MBA research report received the Investec Securities Prize for the Best Research in the field of Investments. He joined the Democratic Party in 1995 and, in 2005, was elected chairman of the DA branch in Sandown, Sandton. After the 2006 municipal elections, he served the City of Johannesburg as a PR councillor on various committees, including housing, finance and economic development and municipal accounts. In 2008 he joined parliament and served on the Finance Committee. Since 2012 he has served as Shadow Minister for SCOPA. Source: www.da.org.za/our_people 
Dion George's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Dion-Travers-George-Attendance-2013 "Dion George") and [2012](/file_archive/Dion-Travers-George-Attendance-2012 "Dion George")

summary:
Mr Gumede has received a diploma in Marketing Management and an advanced diploma in Economic Policy. Politically active since the 1980’s, he has been a member of the UDF, the ANC Underground and was a founding member of the Congress of South African Trade Unions (COSATU). Mr Gumede has been a member of the Portfolio Committee on Trade and Industry, the Portfolio Committee on Labour and the Portfolio Committee on Minerals and Energy. 

Donald Mlindwa Gumede's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/donald-mlindwa-gumede-attendance-2013 "donald mlindwa gumede attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/donald-mlindwa-gumede-attendance-2012 "donald mlindwa gumede attendance").

summary:
Ms Ramodibe received her Business Studies Certificate from Damelin College. She was a member of the Portfolio Committee on Trade and Industry, the Select Committee on Public Enterprises and the Select Committee of Economic and Foreign Affairs. She has served as the African National Congress Women’s League (ANCWL) Western Cape Chairperson, the ANC Deputy Chairperson of Gauteng and regularly works with Trade unions and civic organisations. 

Dorothy Mapula Ramodibe's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/dorothy-mapula-ramodibe-attendance-2013 "Ramodibe Attendance 2013") and [2012](/file_archive/dorothy-mapula-ramodibe-attendance-2012 "Ramodibe Attendance 2012").

Ms Dlakude has been serving the ANC in various structures for the past 18 years. Her previous positions include Treasurer of the ANC Youth League (Ehlanzeni Region), ANC Branch Secretary for a period of six terms and member of the ANC Regional Executive Committee. She matriculated from Mjokwane Senior Secondary School and is currently qualifying in the fields of cost and management accounting, human resources and public leadership and governance. She has been a Member of Parliament since 2010 and has served as the Deputy Chief Whip of the ANC.

name: Ebrahim Ismail Ebrahim
summary:
Deputy Minister Ebrahim is a member of the African National Congress (ANC) National Executive Committee (NEC). Born on 01 July 1937, he joined the liberation movement as a youth activist in 1952, and participated in the Congress of the People Campaign, which adopted the Freedom Charter in 1955. An ex-combatant of Umkhonto Wesizwe, he was arrested and charged under the Sabotage Act in 1961. Sentenced to 15 years imprisonment at Robben Island, he was released in 1979. He went to exile on instruction of the ANC in 1980. The Deputy Minister holds a Bachelor of Arts and a B.Com Degrees from the University of South Africa. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Ebrahim Ismail Ebrahim's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/ebrahim-ismail-ebrahim-attendance-2013 "ebrahim ismail ebrahim attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/ebrahim-ismail-ebrahim-attendance-2012 "ebrahim ismail ebrahim attendance").

name: Ebrahim Patel
summary: Mr Patel has an extensive amount of experience and accomplishments. He has been heavily involved in labour-government issues as he was the Chief Negotiator on the Labour Relations Act of 1995 and the acting (as of 2014) President of the South African Labour Research Institute. He is also involved in higher education, working with multiply universities. He has been Chief Negotiator for the National Bargaining Council for the Clothing Industry (2002) and the National Textile Bargaining Council (2003). He served as the Minister of Economic Development from 2009 – 2014. (Source: anc.org.za)

name: Elizabeth Dipuo Peters
summary:
Minister Peters was born on 13 May 1960. She holds a Bachelor of Arts degree in Social Work from University of the North obtained in 1987. Between 1994 and 1997, she was Member of Parliament during which time she served in the Portfolio Committees on Home Affairs, Public Works, Social Services and Health. The Minister returned to the NC where she served in various portfolios including health, and also as the Premier. Prior to being moved to the Transport portfolio, she was Minister of the Energy Department since 2009. She holds various leadership and development certificates from notable institutions as Havana in Cuba, the University of Cape Town and the University of the Western Cape. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Elizabeth Dipuo Peters' plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](file_archive/elizabeth-dipuo-peters-attendance-2013 "Peters Attendance 2013") and [2012](/file_archive_elizabeth-dipuo-peters-attendance-2012 "Peters Attendence 2012").

name: Elizabeth Thabethe
summary:
Deputy Minister Thabethe was born on 26 September 1959 and had been a Member of Parliament since 1994. She completed a Certificate in Economics with University of South Africa (UNISA) and an Advanced Diploma in Economics in 2008. She was a Co-coordinator of the East Rand Women’s League RTT structure, a member of ANC National Parliamentary Caucus, Gauteng Provincial Whip and a House Whip from 1996 to 2004. She Chaired the Portfolio Committee on Environmental Affairs and Tourism between 2004 and June 2005, but also was a Member of the Committees on Labour and Trade and Industry. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Elizabeth Thabethe's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Elizabeth-Thabethe-Attendance-2013 "Elizabeth Thabethe") and [2012](/file_archive/Elizabeth-Thabethe-Attendance-2012 "Elizabeth Thabethe").

name: Elliot Mshiyeni Sogoni
summary:
Mr Sogoni has been a Member of Parliament since 2004 and is an avid supporter of SARHWU - he has served as their Treasurer and Secretary, and has written a publication on their history. Mr. Sogoni has also worked as the ANC Chairperson of the Vosloorus branch, and was also a Member of the Standing Committee on Finance. 

Elliot Mshiyeni Sogoni's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Elliot-Mshiyeni-Sogoni-Attendance-2013 "Elliot Mshiyeni Sogoni") and [2012](/file_archive/Elliot-Mshiyeni-Sogoni-Attendance-2012 "Elliot Mshiyeni Sogoni").

name: Elsie Mmathulare Coleman
summary:
Ms Coleman holds a degree in Developmental Studies at UWC, a certificate in Public Relations from Damelin, and a certificate in Finance & Economic with UNISA. She also holds several Certificates of Attendance from various academic institutions. Embarking on her political career in the early 1990s, Ms Coleman has since played a very active role in government, serving as the Portfolio Committee of Local Government and Housing Chair, the MEC for Health (2003-04), Finance (2004-08) and Education (2008-09) among other roles. She is currently the Chairperson of the PC on Economic Development. Source: ANC (www.anc.org.za) 

Elsie Mmathulare Coleman's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/elsie-mmathulare-coleman-attendance-2013 "elsie mmathulare coleman attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/elsie-mmathulare-coleman-attendance-2012 "elsie mmathulare coleman attendance").

summary:
Emma More's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Emma-More-Attendance-2013 "Emma More") and [2012](/file_archive/Emma-More-Attendance-2012 "Emma More")

Ms More was born and grew up in Soweto. After completing her secondary education in 1991 she furthered her studies at Technikon Witwatersrand. She qualified as a radiographer and completed a number of other qualifications in HIV/AIDS Counseling and Management, African Management, Hospital Management, Public Financial Management and is currently busy completing a Masters Degree in Public Development and Management at WITS University. After a successful career in the public health sector, Emma made her entry into South African politics and joined the DA in 2008. She was initially involved with canvassing work for the party in Kempton Park and managed seven stations for Ward 58 during the 2009 elections. Emma is currently appointed as the Shadow Deputy Minister of Social Development for the DA.

summary: Minister Mthethwa was born on 23 January 1967 and had been a Member of Parliament since 2002. The Minister holds a Diploma in Community Development from University of Natal; a Certificate in Mining Engineering from University of Johannesburg and a Certificate in Communications and Leadership from Rhodes University. As Member of Parliament, he had served as Chairperson for Minerals and Energy Portfolio Committee from 2004 to 2008; and as Chief Whip of the ANC in 2008. He also served on the Board of Directors of 2010 FIFA World Cup Local Organisation Committee. Source: (info.gov.za)

summary:
While in exile Mr Ngcobo completed his MSc programme in the area of In-Core Fuel Management and Control of Nuclear Reactors of VVER-type at the University of Sofia. He was awarded the City Honour by the City Council of Pietermaritzburg for his publications in the field of Nuclear Science and Engineering, as well as for his contribution in local community development programmes. Hon Ngcobo has served as the Chairperson of the Portfolio Committee on Science and Technology and the Chairperson of the Portfolio Committee on Minerals and Energy.

summary:
Ms. Faith Claudine Bikani is a current member of the PC on Health and the PC on Public Service and Administration. She holds a diploma in Nursing Administration, Nursing Midwifery, Psychiatry and General Nursing Science as well as an Advanced Nursing Degree, a certificate in Computer Skills and a certificate in Skills Development. Bikani is the current ANC branch deputy secretary, a PEC and PWC member and the head of the Organising and Campaigns sub-committee. Ms. Bikani was previously a BEC Member, the Deputy Secretary in the Joyce Boom Branch and the ANC WL Regional Secretary. Source: ANC (www.anc.org.za)

name: Fatima Hajaig
summary: Ms Hajaig has been a MP since 1994. She has served in various positions in Parliament including the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs, Member of Portfolio Committee on Trade and Industry, has been part of the JMC on JMC Improvement of Quality of Life and the Status of Women, Member of the Portfolio Committee on Foreign Affairs,  Portfolio Committee on Justice and Constitutional Development, Portfolio Committee on Foreign Affairs (Sub-Committee on International Affairs), the Pan African committee on Justice and Human Rights, SADC-PF Committee on Inter-Parliamentary Cooperation, the Parliamentary Group on International Relations and Parliamentarians For Global Action. Her political career includes membership of the ANCWYL Executive in Gauteng, taking part in the Kempton Park negotiations and membership of the UDF, Patriotic Front, Transvaal Indian Congress and the Transvaal Youth Congress. (Source: anc.org.za)

name: Fatima Ismail Chohan
summary:
Deputy Minister Chohan has been Member of Parliament since 1996 and has been the Deputy Minister of Home Affairs since 2010. Chohan holds a B.Proc degree from University of Witwatersrand, was admitted to the side bar in 1998 and is pursuing a Masters Degree in Constitutional Law with Rhodes University. She chaired various Portfolio Committees such as Basic Education, Justice and Constitutional Development and Public Enterprises. Deputy Minister Chohan served as a Legal Advisor in the Gauteng Legislature and Parliamentary Representative on the Magistrates Commission and later became Chairperson of the Western Cape Provincial Committee of the Magistrates Commission. Source: (http://www.info.gov.za)

summary:
Fikile April Mbalula's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Fikile-April-Mbalula-Attendance-2013 "Fikile April Mbalula Attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/Fikile-April-Mbalula-Attendance-2012 "Fikile April Mbalula Attendance")

Mr Mbalula has served as the Minister of Sport and has held various leadership positions since his entry into the South African political arena. He held the positions as President of the Botshabelo Youth Congress from 1986 to 1987, President of the ANCYL from 2004 to 2008 and Secretary-General of the ANCYL from 1998 to 2004. In addition to this, he was appointed as the Area Manager for the United Democratic Front in 1989, Affiliate Member of Socialist International and the Coordinator of the South African Medical and Dental Association. Mr Mbalula holds a Masters Degree in Economics and completed training in Leadership Skills and Counseling.

name: Gaolatlhe Godfrey Oliphant
summary:
Deputy Minister Oliphant, could not have occupied a better portfolio than Mineral Resources. Born in Warrenton, in the Diamonds’ province of the Northern Cape, he is currently a member of Central Committee of the South African Communist Party and member of the Task Team of the African National Congress (ANC) in North West Province. He had been a Member of Parliament since 1994 and had served as Chairperson of the Portfolio Committees on Public Works and the Science and Technology, Labour, and Minerals and Energy. He matriculated at Huhudi High School in the Vryburg area and had pursued studies in Economics. He has held various senior position with the tripartite alliance structures, including serving as Vice President of the Congress of South African Trade Union (COSATU). Source: (info.gov.za)

name: George Gaolatlhe Boinamo
summary:
Born in 1948, Mr. George Boinamo is the current Shadow Deputy Minister of Co-operative Governance and Traditional Affairs. Mr. Boinamo completed training to become a teacher at Hebron College of Education in 1978, completed his BA Ed. at the University of the Witwatersrand and then obtained a Masters in Education in 1997. After several years of teaching, Boinamo joined the DA in 2003 and became an MP in 2004 where he served as spokeperson on education. He was re-elected to parliament in 2009. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za) 

George Boinamo's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/George-Boinamo-attendance-2013 "George Boinamo Attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/George-Boinamo-attendance-2012 "George Boinamo Attendance")

name: Gerhardus Cornelius Oosthuizen
summary:
Deputy Minister Oosthuizen was born on 10 May 1957. He became the Deputy Minister of Sport and Recreation in 2004. Mr Oosthuizen was a member of the South African Air Force up to the Rank of Captain from 1980 until 1983 and then became self employed from 1984 to 1987. A true “Nat”, he became a Member of Parliament in 1987. The Deputy Minister holds a Bachelor of Arts degree in Political Science from Rand Afrikaans University (RAU); a Bachelor of Arts Honours degree in Development Studies from RAU, Suma Cum Laude and various other courses and study tours. Between the years 2001 and 2004, he served as an ANC Member in the Defence and Correctional Services Portfolio Committees. Source: (info.gov.za)

name: Gloria Mary Borman
summary:
Ms. Borman was an MP from 1999-2004. She was a member of the Provincial and Local Portfolio Committee, the Social Development Portfolio Committee and the Public Enterprises Portfolio Committee among others. Ms. Borman joined the ANC in 2005 and won the ward for the ANC from DA and served as ward councilor from 2006-2009. She has taken courses in matrix exemption and bookkeeping. Currently Ms. Borman is a member of the PC on Human Settlement. Source: ANC (www.anc.org.za)

name: Grace Kekulu Tseke
summary:
Ms Tseke has served as a Member of the Portfolio Committees on Transportation and PC Women, Youth, Children and People with Disability. Prior to serving as an MP, she served as an ANC Ward Councilor (2000 – 2005); Maretele PCO Administrator (2004 – 2009); ANC Greenmara Branch Secretary (2001 – 2004); Deputy Branch Secretary (200-6 – 2008); and ANC WL branch Chairperson (2001 – 2002). She has received a University Diploma in Education (1995 – 1997); Diploma in Business Computing (2004); and a Certificate in Managing the Employment Process (2006). (Source: anc.org.za)

Grace Kekulu Tseke's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Grace-Kekulu-Tseke-Attendance-2013 "Grace Kekulu Tseke") and [2012](/file_archive/Grace-Kekulu-Tseke-Attendance-2012 "Grace Kekulu Tseke").

name: Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor
summary:
Minister Pandor was born on 07 December 1953. She holds two Masters degrees in Education (University of London), and Linguistics (University of Stellenbosch). She had been a Member of Parliament since 1994, during which time she served as caucus whip; Chairperson of the NCOP, and as well as Member of the Portfolio Committee on Education. Minister Pandor taught at such distinguished institutions as Ernest Bevin School, Taung College of Education, University of Bophuthatswana, and the University of Cape Town. In the mid to late 90s, she served as both the Deputy Chairperson and Chairperson of the Tertiary Education Fund of South Africa (TEFSA). She was Minister of Science and Technology in the previous administration. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor-attendance-2013 "Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor Attendance 2013") and [2012](/file_archive/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor-attendance "Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor Attandance 2012").

name: Grant Trevor Snell
summary:
Mr Snell was a Member of the Eastern Cape Legislature from 1999 to 2009. He became a Presiding Officer for the Whips Committee Member of Executive Committee, a Deputy Chairperson of the Committee of Chairpersons, the Chairperson of Budget and Oversight Committee, Chairperson of the NCOP Business Committee, a Chairperson of the Review of Rules Committee, a Member of the Rules Committee and a Member of the Programming Committee. Mr Snell holds a certificate in Business Management from Rhodes University and cites his personal interests as gardening and reading. Source: www.anc.org.za/caucus

Grant Trevor Snell's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Grant-Trevor-Snell-Attendance-2013 "Grant Trevor Snell") and [2012](/file_archive/Grant-Trevor-Snell-Attendance-2012 "Grant Trevor Snell").

name: Gratitude Magwanishe
summary:
Deputy Minister Magwanishe has served a Member of Parliament since 1999. He holds Master of Business Administration (MBA) from the regent Business School in 2006; a Bachelor of Science in Jurisprudence degree in 2001 and a Certificate on Strategic Leadership Programme from the WITS Business School in 2003. He has also served as Whip in various committees and as Cluster Whip for Justice and Constitutional Development; Defence; Home Affairs; Foreign Affairs; Safety and Security; Correctional Services and Intelligence from 2004 to 2009 and as Deputy Chief Whip of the Ruling Party in the National Assembly from October 2008 until his re-deployment as a Deputy Minister. He was born in 1973. Source: (info.gov.za). 

Gratitude Magwanishe's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Gratitude-Magwanishe-Attendance-2013 "Gratitude Magwanishe") and [2012](/file_archive/Gratitude-Magwanishe-Attendance-2012 "Gratitude Magwanishe Attendance").

summary:
Gregory Rudy Krumbock's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Gregory-Rudy-Krumbock-Attendance-2013 "Gregory Krumbock") and [2012](/file_archive/Gregory-Rudy-Krumbock-Attendance-2012 "Gregory Krumbock").

Gregory completed his post-secondary education at the University of Cape Town where he attained a BCom degree.  In 1998 he was appointed as the Executive Director of the Democratic Party of which his main responsibility was that of managing the party’s 1999 General Election Campaign. He was first elected to Parliament in 1999 as a representative of Mpumalanga and KwaZulu-Natal in 2004. Gregory is presently serving his third term as the Provincial Chairperson of KZN, consultant to the CEO in respect of election matters and Shadow Minister of Economic Development for DA. Source: DA (www.da.org.za)

name: Gugile Ernest Nkwinti
summary:
Minister Nkwinti was born on 18 December 1948. He holds a Masters degree in Public Policy and Management from the University of London and a Bachelor of Administration degree specialising in Political Science, Public Administration and Applied Economics from the University of South Africa. Prior to his appointment as a Minister he was Speaker of the EC Provincial Legislature from the 1994 to 1999; MEC for Housing 1999 to 2005; and MEC for Agriculture EC from 2005 to 2009. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Gugile Ernest Nkwinti's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/gugile-ernest-nkwinti-attendance-2013 "gugile ernest nkwinti attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/gugile-ernest-nkwinti-attendance-2012 "gugile ernest nkwinti attendance").

name: Hargreaves Tisetso Magama
summary:
Mr Magama has had an active, dynamic, and often rewarding experience in politics. Highlights of his career include: Deputy Chairperson of SAYCO (1987-90), Co-ordinator of the RELEASE MANDELA Campaign (1988-89), Chairperson of the Cosas Upington Region (1990-91), Provincial Education Secretary Cosas, Northern Cape (1990-1992) and Regional Secretary of the ANC Siyanda region (1997-1998). Mr Magama also authored the paper Perspectives & Analyses (2006).

Hargreaves Tisetso Magama's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Hargreaves-Tisetso-Magama-Attendance-2013 "Hargreaves Tisetso Magama Attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/Hargreaves-Tisetso-Magama-Attendance-2012 "Hargreaves Tisetso Magama Attendance").

summary:
Helena Claudina Van Schalkwyk's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Helena-Claudina-Van-Schalkwyk-Attendance-2013 "Helena Claudina Van Schalkwyk") and [2012](/file_archive/Helena-Claudina-Van-Schalkwyk-Attendance-2012 "Helena Claudina Van Schalkwyk").

Dr van Schalkwyk was born and raised in the Eastern Cape. After completing her high school career she furthered her studies at Stellenbosch University and graduated with a BA degree. She obtained her PhD in Biblical Science from the University of South Africa in 2003. She has extensive teaching experience and first became involved in South African politics in 2006. On her entry to politics Dr van Schalkwyk was elected as a councilor of the Hantam Municipality and served as the vice chairperson in the Hantam-Hoogland constituency from 2006 to 2007.  She is currently appointed as the Shadow Deputy Minister of Arts and Culture and also serving as the vice chairperson of the DA’s local branch in Calvinia. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za).

Helen was born in the Eastern Cape and obtained a teaching diploma from Zonnebloem College in Cape Town and completed diplomas in business management and advanced bookkeeping.  She first entered the political arena in 1992 after joining the DP.  In 2000 she was appointed as s regional organiser for the DA and was subsequently promoted to Acting Director of the DA in the Western Region.  She was first elected to Parliament in 2004 in the capacity of member of the National Council of Provinces.  Prior to her current position of Shadow Minister for Women, Children and People with Disabilities, she was Shadow Minister of Social Development of the DA. Source: DA (www.da.org.za).

name: Hendrietta Ipeleng Bogopane-Zulu
summary:
Deputy Minister Bogopane-Zulu had been a Member of Parliament since 1999. She served both the South African Federation of Disabled People and the South Africa National AIDS Council since 1994 and 2000 respectively. She had served both Parliament and Government in various portfolios, and such institutions as the National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac); South African Qualification Authority (SAQA); Disabled Children's Action Group;; and the World Blind Union. Prior to her appointment as Deputy Minister of Women, Children and Persons with Disability, she served as a Deputy Minister of Public Works. She holds BTech Degree. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Hendrietta Ipeleng Bogopane-Zulu's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/hendrietta-ipeleng-bogopane-zulu-attendance-2013 "hendrietta ipeleng bogopane-zulu attendance") and [2012](/file_archive/hendrietta-ipeleng-bogopane-zulu-attendance-2012 "hendrietta ipeleng bogopane-zulu attendance").

summary:
Hendrik Cornelius Schmidt's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/Hendrik-Cornelius-Schmidt-Attendance-2013 "Hendrick Cornelius Schmidt") and [2012](/file_archive/Hendrik-Cornelius-Schmidt-Attendance-2012 "Hendrik Cornelius Schmidt").

Hendrik was born in Klerksdorp. Upon completing his secondary education, Mr Schmidt studies law. He completed a B.Luris and an LLB degree from UNISA, an LLM from RAU and an MPhil. Mr Schmidt has extensive experience in the South African justice system, as he worked for the Department of Justice as a public prosecutor and then as a State advocate, and later as Senior State Advocate. He started his political career working as councilor in 1999 and was first elected to Parliament in 1999. He was appointed as the DA’s spokesperson for Minerals and Energy from 2004 to 2009. Hendrik is currently appointed as the Shadow Deputy Minister of Mineral Resources for the DA. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za).

name: Hendrik Petrus Leonardus Van Der Linde
Hlengiwe Buhle Mkhize
summary:
Deputy Minister Mkhize was born on 06 September 1952. She served as a Member of Parliament since 2009. A founding member, and trustee, of the Children and Violence Trust since 1995, had been a trustee of the Malibongwe Business Trust from 2005. Professor Mkhize holds a BA degree in Psychology, Social Work and Sociology (University of Zululand); BA Hons (Psychology) and a Masters in Clinical Psychology from the University of Natal. She was a senior lecturer and researcher at Wits from 1990 until 1995. She was a board member of the South African Prisoner's Organisation for Human Rights from 1994 to 1995; Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) Commissioner and Chairperson of the Reparations and Rehabilitation committee from 1995 to 2003. Prior to her appointment, Prof Mkhize was ambassador to the Netherlands, and had a short stint as Deputy Minister for Correctional Services. Source: (info.gov.za)

name: Holmes Peter Maluleka
summary:
An MP since 2004, Mr. Maluleka has maintained an optimistic view of South Africa’s future, affirming that he is “confident” of the country’s’ future and believes it will continue to “improve.” He has earned both a Local Government and Administration Certificate (UNISA), along with a Democracy and Local Goverance certificate (Univ. of Stockholm). Mr Maluleka has served as the Speaker of the Tshwane Municipality, Executive Chairperson of the Greater Pretoria Municipality, and the Mamelodi Civic Organisation Deputy Chairperson.

summary:
Ms Malgas is the Chairperson of the Basic Education Portfolio Committee, and has also served on the Committees for Women, Children, Youth and Persons with Disabilities, Social Development, and International Relations. She was a teacher before she became a Member of Parliament. As a teacher, she was involved in sport, serving as a referee for field events on a national and international level.

Mr Ollis was born in East London in 1970. He completed his tertiary education through the Baptist Theological College, University of Zululand and attained a Master of Arts degree from WITS University. Prior to joining South African politics, Mr Ollis worked in the higher education sector. He joined the Democratic Party (DP) in 1999 and was elected to the City Council in 2005. In 2006 he was re-elected as a ward councilor and has worked for the DA’s fundraising department and executed duties on the Gauteng South Regional Executive. He was first elected to Parliament in 2009 and is currently serving as the DA’ Shadow Minister of Transport. Source: DA (www.da.org.za).

summary: Mr. Jac Bekker was first elected to parliament in 2009 and previously served as the party's chief whip in the Eden District municipality. Source: DA (www.da.org.za)

summary: James Jim Skosana's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/James-Jim-Skosana-Attendance-2013 "James Jim Skosana") and [2012](/file_archive/James-Jim-Skosana-Attendance-2012 "James Jim Skosana").

summary:
James Robert Bourne Lorimer's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/James-Robert-Bourne-Lorimer-Attendance-2013 "James Robert Bourne Lorimer") and [2012](/file_archive/James-Robert-Bourne-Lorimer-Attendance-2012 "James Robert Bourne Lorimer").

Mr Lorimer was born in Johannesburg in 1962. He completed a BA degree at the University of the Witswatersrand and worked as a freelance journalist whilst studying. He worked as a news anchor on radio 702 in 1994 and started Network Radio Services in the same year, executing duties as its Chief Executive Officer. He became involved in politics in 2003 after being appointed as Tony Leon’s Media Director. He was subsequently promoted to the national media team fulfilling the role of Media and Research Director for the DA caucus in the Gauteng Legislature. James is currently appointed as the DA’s Shadow Minister of Mineral Resources. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za)

name: James Selfe
summary:
James Selfe's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/James-Selfe-Attendance-2013 "James Selfe") and [2012](/file_archive/James-Selfe-Attendance-2012 "James Selfe").

James was born in Pretoria and attended Bishops boarding School in Cape Town. Upon completing his secondary education he was called up for military training in the South African National Defence Force anti-aircraft division and progressed to the rank of Lieutenant Colonel. James started his political career in late 1978 by working in the research department of the Progressive Federal Party (PFP). He became the party’s Director of Communication in 1988. He joined the Democratic Party in 1992 in the capacity of Executive Director. After his election to Parliament in 1999 he became the party’s spokesperson on Provincial and Local Government. In 2004 he was re-elected to Parliament and became responsible for the Correctional Services Portfolio. He assumed his current post of Shadow Minister of Correctional Services upon his re-election to Parliament in 2009. (http://www.da.org.za).

name: Jeffrey Thamsanqa Radebe
summary:
Minister Radebe was born on 18 February 1953. He holds a B.Juris degree from the University of Zululand; LLM in International Law from Leipzig University. He had served the ANC as Policy Unit head, a position he continues to hold. But had been member of the NEC – ANC’s decision making structure in between conferences - since 1991. He underwent military training with Umkhonto weSizwe (MK), and was once arrested and convicted under the Terrorism Act. He served as Minister of Public Works, Public Enterprises, and Transport prior to his appointment as Minister of Justice and Constitutional Development. Source: (info.gov.za) 

Jeffrey Thamsanqa Radebe's plenary attendance record for Feb-Apr [2013](/file_archive/jeffrey-thamsanqa-radebe-attendance-2013 "JT Radebe Attendance 2013") and [2012](/file_archive/jeffrey-thamsanqa-radebe-attendance-2012 "JT Radebe Attendance 2012").

name: Jeremy Patrick Cronin
summary:
Deputy Minister Cronin was born on 12 September 1949. He currently is the Deputy General-Secretary of South African Communist Party (SACP), a position he has held since 1995. He became a Member of Parliament since 1999. His illustrious political career dates back into time, such that he Co-Convened the Reconstruction and Development Programme Drafting Committee and was a member of the negotiating Team at Convention for a Democratic South Africa (CODESA). The Deputy Minister lectured at UCT between 1973 and 1976; but also was Editor of the African Communist Magazine. Prior to his current appoint, he was Deputy Minister for Transport. Source: (info.gov.za)

He has been an activist, exile and political prisoner, the latter of which inspired his personal memoirs published in Robben Island manuals. Mr Maake has been a member of the Portfolio Committee on Trade and Industry and has served as the Premier Director of Strategic Planning at the Office of Limpopo.

He was a political activist and is considered a revolutionary who was at the forefront of the people’s struggle for liberation during Apartheid. He holds a Masters degree in Governance and Political Transformation from the University of the Free State, as well as two Diplomas in Executive Management and Transformation from Harvard University.

summary:
Ms Fubbs was born on 30 November 1944. She received her BA from the University of South Africa (Unisa). An MP since 2004, she has served as the Whip of the Joint Budget Committee (NA and NCOP), the Whip of the Economic Transformation Cluster and a Member of the Portfolio Committee on Finance. Ms Fubbs also chaired the Standing Committee on Finance and Economic Affairs and was the Deputy Chair of the Internal Audit in the Gauteng Legislature.

The current Chancellor of the University of Zululand (UniZulu), studied Library Science at UniZulu; Bachelor of Arts degree in International Politics and African Politics from Unisa. He was arrested for ANC activities in May 1976 and was sentenced to ten years on Robben Island in June 1977. He played a key role in peace initiatives in Natal during the late 80s. He served as MEC for Transport in KwaZulu-Natal in 1994-2004; and was a member of the KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Executive Committee and the Provincial Working Committee of the ANC from 1994 to 2008. Mr De Lange was the former Deputy Minister for Justice and Constitutional Development (2004-09), was the Head of the Office of Criminal Justice Review (2006-09) and was Commissioner on the Judicial Service Commission (1996-04). He is currently a member of the Subcommittee on  Social Transformation and ANC NEC.

From 2001 to 2004 he served as an MEC for Agriculture and Tourism, and Environmental Affairs. He is currently a Member of Parliament in the National Assembly and has served on the Portfolio Committees for Sport and Recreation, Home Affairs, and Housing. Dr Kloppers-Lourens joined the DA in 2005 and was elected to Parliament in 2009. She was born in and raised in Vanderbijlpark in Gauteng. After completing her secondary education she continued her studies at the University of Pretoria where she completed a BA and Honors degree in History. In addition to this, she completed a Master’s and Doctorate degree in Education at RAU, a LLB at UNISA and the AIPSA Diploma for Insolvency Practitioners at the University of Pretoria. She was previously employed as a chief researcher and developer to the Bureau for Curriculum Development and Evaluation, Public Relations Officer for Perskor Publishers and later Academic Publisher for Lex Patria Publishers. Reverend Kenneth Meshoe started out as a teacher before embarking on a successful career as a pastor and political leader. Rev Meshoe founded the African Christian Democratic Party in December 1993, and has been a member of the National Assembly since 1994. Rev Meshoe was awarded an Honorary Doctorate (Doctor of Humane Letters) by Bethel Christian College of Riverside, California, USA in 1994 and was also appointed to serve as an Associate Member on the Board of Regents of Bethel College

name: Kenneth Sililo Mubu
summary:
Mr Mubu was born in Lusaka, Zambia. He holds a BA in Education from the University of Zambia, and also a Master of Arts (MA) degree in Journalism/Public Relations from Ball State University, Muncie, Indiana, USA, and a Postgraduate Diploma in Management from Leicester University, United Kingdom as well as a Certificate in Public Relations Management from the Public Relations Institute of Southern Africa (PRiSA). Mr Mubu played a critical role in voter education in the first democratic elections in 1994, informing communities of their voting rights. Under his leadership, the Turfloop Foundation realised the completion of EDUPARK, a multi-institution project outside of Polokwane. During his tunure at TSA a number of important projects were achieved on the African continent, one of these being the Southern Sudan Capacity and Institution Building initiative. Source: www.da.org.za/our_people

name: Knowledge Malusi Nkanyezi Gigaba
summary:
Minister Gigaba was born on 30 August 1971. He holds a Bachelor of Pedagogics in Education, and a Master of Arts Degree in Social Policy from UDW. He joined the African National Congress (ANC), the South African Communist Party (SACP) and the ANCYL in 1990 and he was one of the founding members of the Education Students Society at UDW. He served as convenor of the Provincial Education Forum, becoming ANC YL president in 1994. He became a Member of Parliament for the ANC in 1999 and during that period he also served as a member of the Trade and Industry Portfolio Committee. Prior being Public Enterprises Minister, he served as Deputy Minister of Home Affairs. Source: (info.gov.za)

summary:
Deputy Minister Bapela took part in the 1976 student uprising. He was a member of the African National Congress (ANC) underground structures from 1979, and also a founding member of United Democratic Front (UDF) in 1983. He was detained several times and appeared in two political trials in Port Elizabeth and Alexandra between 1986 and 1987 and between 1987 and 1990. The Deputy Minister holds a Diploma in Journalism and various other Certificates such varied fields as community and organisational development; safety and security; and policy development. As a Member of Parliament he sat in the Portfolio Committee of Foreign Affairs and Trade and Industry, before becoming Deputy Minister for DPME. Source: (info.gov.za)

name: Koti Jacob Dikobo
summary:
Jacob Koti Dikobo was born on 22 April 1962completed his tertiary education at the University of the North and graduated with the Bachelor of Education (B.Ed) and a Bachelor of Education in Pedagogy (B.A. (Paed). While he was at university, Dikobo became an active member of the Black Consciousness Movement (BCM) and served in its leadership structures. He served as secretary and later chairman of the Turfloop Branch of the Azanian Students Movement (AZASM).  
Mr Dikobo was also involved in a number of youth related religious organizations and upon completion of his studies, went on to work as a teacher and later a school principal. 
After the formation of the Azanian People’s Organisation (AZAPO), Dikobo served as the party’s Secretary of the Seshego Branch rising through the ranks to the position of Secretary of the Northern Transvaal Region. Around the same time, he became Secretary of the Seshego Education Watchdog Committee (SEWACO). Dikobo later became AZAPO’s Vice Chairman and served as a member of the party’s Central Committee.
He became actively involved in the underground structures of AZAPO, the Black Consciousness Movement of Azania (BCMA) and later joined the Azanian National Liberation Army (AZANLA). He was part of AZAPO’s delegation to a tri-lateral meeting between AZAPO, BCMA and the Pan-Africanist Congress (PAC) in Kadoma, Zimbabwe. 
Dikobo also became an active trade unionist. He served as Vice- President of the National Professional Teachers Organisation of South Africa (NAPTOSA) and as a Central Committee member of the National Council of Trade Unions (NACTU).
After the Professional Educators Union (PEU) was launched in 1998, Dikobo served as Vice-chairman of the Pietersburg District and later as the union’s President. He also served as Vice President of the Confederation of South African Workers Union (CONSAWU) after its launch in 2003. He was also elected President of the Association of Non-Aligned Teacher Unions in Southern Africa (ANTUSA) at its founding in December 2007 in Kabwe, Zambia, a position he held until he relinquished it on his election as AZAPO President.
Dikobo is also a member of various institutions. He served as a member of the National Board for Further Education and Training (NBFET), the NEDLAC Development Chamber, and ETDP-SETA. He served as a Chairman of the College Council of the Capricorn College for Further Education and Training and Secretary of the College Council of Kwena Moloto College.
In March 2010, Dikobo was elected as the President of AZAPO succeeding Mosibudi Mangena. He is also the party’s sole Member of Parliament.Source: (sahistory.org.za)

Mr Greyling is the Shadow Minister for Energy. He is also the Chief Whip of the parliamentary caucus as well as the National Policy Convenor. Mr Greyling’s major areas of interest are environment, rural development and energy. Before assuming public office, he was the Regional Programme Manager for GLOBE Southern Africa, where he was in charge of capacitating Members of Parliament in the Southern African region on environmental and sustainable development issues. Mr. Greyling has an honours degree in African Studies from the University of Cape Town and is presently completing a Masters programme on sustainable energy.

Mr Diale joined the ANC in 1956 and has been a Member of Parliament since the first democratic election in 1994. Mr Diale has completed a Junior Certificate. Since his entry into South African politics he has been a member in various political formations, including the South African Congress of Trade Unions. He has performed duties in the Advice Centre in the ANC Jane Furse Branch and has served as a Regional Executive Committee member. He is currently serving on the Parliamentary Committees on Correctional Services, Defence and Military Veterans, and Safety and Security respectively. Mr Diale’s policy interests include control of the economy by the working class and poverty eradication.

name: Lindiwe Nonceba Sisulu
summary:
Minister Sisulu was born on 10 May 1954. She holds an MA in History and an Mphil from the Centre for Southern African Studies, University of York. She was detained for political activism in 1975, and upon release she joined Umkhonto we Sizwe (MK). A keen student of history, she specialised on intelligence matters while undergoing military training. She taught history at various institutions in the southern Africa region during the 80s. She returned to SA in 1990 and became Personal Assistant to President Jacob Zuma as the (ANC) Head of Intelligence. Prior to her appointment as Minister of Public Service and Administration, she served government as a Deputy Minister of Home Affairs; Minister of Intelligence; Housing; and Defence. Source: (info.gov.za)

name: Lourens Lemmer Bosman
summary:
Dr. Lourie Bosman is the current shadow Deputy Minister of Higher Education and Training. Dr. Bosman practiced as a pharmacist from 1965-1978, began farming cattle and maize in 1968 and ran a Brahman Stud on his farms in the Warmbath district. He has undertaken many roles over the years, becoming director of Northern Transvaal Co-op from 1990-1994, Chairperson of Waterberg/Warmbaths DAU from 1984-1990 and Transvaal Agricultural Union Northern Region Chairperson from 1988-1993. Furthermore, he was President of Agri Mpumalanga from 1998-2004, Deputy President of Agri SA from 2000-2004 and President of Agri SA from 2004-2008. He has served on numerous committees and in his community in various capacities over the years. A long standing member of the DA, Dr. Bosman was elected to Parliament in 2009. Source: DA (http://www.da.org.za)

summary:
Minister Xingwana was born on 23 September 1955. She holds BSc degree (Wits); Post Graduate Diploma in Rural Development (University of Zimbabwe), and a Post Graduate Diploma in Economic Principles (University of London). She had been a Member of Parliament since 1993, and had served the ANC and its Women’s League in various capacities. She has served in various Portfolio Committees as sport, environmental affairs and tourism, defence, and minerals and energy. She worked for the South African Council of Churches as Director for Women's Development Programmes in 1987. Minister Xingwana also headed ministries of Agriculture and Land Affairs and Arts and Culture prior to her current portfolio. Source: (info.gov.za)

summary:
